menu "Home Assistant client"

config HA_CLIENT_WIFI_SSID
    string "WiFi SSID"
    default ""
    help
        WPA2-Personal SSID. Leave empty to skip WiFi bring-up; the
        screen will show a "configure WiFi" message.

config HA_CLIENT_WIFI_PASSWORD
    string "WiFi password"
    default ""
    help
        WPA2-Personal passphrase. Stored in the local sdkconfig only,
        which is gitignored.

config HA_CLIENT_SERVER_URL
    string "Home Assistant base URL"
    default "http://192.168.1.232:8123"
    help
        Base URL of the Home Assistant server. Include scheme and port;
        a trailing slash is optional. Plain HTTP on the LAN — HTTPS
        would need a cert bundle and is not configured.

config HA_CLIENT_TOKEN
    string "Long-lived access token"
    default ""
    help
        Home Assistant long-lived access token. The REST API does NOT
        accept a username/password — those only log into the web UI.

        To create one: log into the web UI, click your user name at the
        bottom-left, open the Security tab, scroll to "Long-lived access
        tokens", and press "Create token". The token is shown once and
        cannot be retrieved afterwards.

        Default lifespan is 10 years, so no refresh logic is needed.

config HA_CLIENT_POLL_INTERVAL_S
    int "Poll interval (seconds)"
    default 10
    range 2 600
    help
        How often to re-render the entity template and refresh the
        screen. One template render is cheap (~2 KB response), so this
        can be far shorter than a per-device polling API would allow.
        Button presses are handled immediately regardless of this value.

config HA_CLIENT_LABEL
    string "Home Assistant label to show"
    default "box3"
    help
        Only entities carrying this label are shown. Create the label in
        Home Assistant (Settings > Areas & labels > Labels), then add it
        to each entity you want on the screen.

        Nothing about the selection lives in this firmware, so labelling
        one more entity makes it appear within one poll — no reflash.

        A label is used rather than a domain sweep because Home Assistant
        exposes no way to tell a real device from an integration's own
        config entities: switch.plug_led and switch.plug_auto_off_enabled
        sit in the same domain and area as switch.plug, with no
        device_class and no entity_category visible to the template API.
        A domain sweep puts all of them on screen; the label puts exactly
        what you picked.

        Supported domains: light, switch (toggle rows) and sensor
        (read-only rows). Labelling an entity of any other domain is
        harmless — it is skipped with a log line.

config HA_CLIENT_MAX_ENTITIES
    int "Max labelled entities"
    default 16
    range 1 32
    help
        Upper bound on labelled entities kept and shown. Also caps the
        rendered template so the response cannot overflow the device's
        buffer. Entities beyond the cap are dropped with a warning in
        the log rather than silently.

endmenu
